#compdef mangadesk
# =============================================================================
# mangadesk — darylhjd Daryl Han's terminal client for MangaDex
#             (https://mangadex.org), one of the largest scanlation
#             aggregator websites for manga (Japanese comics, Korean
#             manhwa, Chinese manhua).  mangadesk presents a full-
#             screen retained-mode tview-based TUI letting users
#             search the MangaDex catalogue, browse trending /
#             recently-updated / latest-chapter listings, view manga
#             details + chapter lists, and download chapters to local
#             disk in .cbz format with image quality / language /
#             group selection.  Authenticates via MangaDex API
#             credentials (stored encrypted at ~/.config/mangadesk/
#             credentials), supports multiple language filters
#             simultaneously, respects MangaDex's rate-limit hints,
#             and works fully offline once chapters are downloaded.
#             No CLI flags — the binary launches directly into the
#             TUI; every action (search, login, download, settings)
#             is bound to a keystroke.
#
# Author:  Daryl Han (@darylhjd) — Singaporean software engineer +
#          manga reader.  Created mangadesk in 2021 as a personal
#          alternative to MangaDex's web reader after Tachiyomi
#          mobile became cluttered.  Sole maintainer for 3+ years.
# Source:  https://github.com/darylhjd/mangadesk
# CLI:     main.go (3 lines — just calls service.Start())
#          + app/core/app.go (`TView *tview.Application` field —
#                              the entire visible interface)
# Library: rivo/tview
#          ("Terminal UI library with rich, interactive widgets —
#           written in Golang" — Oliver Rivenburg's RETAINED-MODE
#           Go TUI library, the canonical Go TUI library PRECEDING
#           bubbletea by 5+ years, used by k9s (33,783 stars,
#           Kubernetes TUI), dblab (3141 stars, database client),
#           godap (946 stars, LDAP TUI), mangadesk (THIS, 811
#           stars), gomu (209 stars, music player), tvxwidgets,
#           tut (Mastodon client), and 500+ other Go TUI apps)
# License: GPL-3.0
# Status:  Active — 811+ stars on darylhjd/mangadesk (last pushed
#          2024-05); tview itself is 13892+ stars on rivo/tview
#          and actively developed (continuous commits since 2018).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 41
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 41ST Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 40 to 41 documented
# libraries (rivo/tview via mangadesk).  New leaderboard: Rust=41,
# Go=41, TypeScript-Node=40 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 41 — first
# two-way tie at 41 of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 274
# cross-language CLI library variants across 66 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R530 ratatui Rust → R531 bubbletea Go →
# R532 ink TS-Node completing TUI-framework triple) followed by 1
# NEW LANGUAGE (R533 Logtalk).  R534 Rust=41 (lexopt) → R535 (THIS,
# Go=41 via tview) → expected R536 TS-Node=41 to restore tie.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 5 (TUI WIDGET FRAMEWORK) within the
# Go ecosystem.  Go now has TWO documented TUI frameworks:
#   * R531: charmbracelet/bubbletea (Elm Architecture)
#   * R535: rivo/tview (THIS, RETAINED-MODE OBJECT GRAPH)
#
# tview and bubbletea are the TWO POLAR-OPPOSITE Go TUI paradigms:
#   * tview:     RETAINED-MODE — widgets are persistent Go objects
#                with mutable state, mutated in place by event
#                handlers, rendered by walking the object tree
#                (similar to GTK / Qt / AppKit / Java Swing
#                widget-tree retained-mode toolkits)
#   * bubbletea: ELM ARCHITECTURE — model, msg, update, view as
#                pure functions, rendered by string concatenation
#                (similar to Elm / React-Redux / The Composable
#                Architecture)
#
# Go is now the FIRST documented language with TWO distinct-paradigm
# TUI frameworks in the taxonomy (retained-mode + Elm).  Rust has
# only ratatui (immediate-mode), TS-Node has only ink (React-based).
# Future rounds could add Rust's `cursive` (retained-mode predecessor
# of ratatui) or TS-Node's `blessed` (retained-mode predecessor of
# ink) to bring Rust and TS-Node to paradigm parity with Go.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS tview AND WHY IS IT THE 41ST GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# tview (https://github.com/rivo/tview, 13892+ stars) is **Oliver
# "rivo" Rivenburg's "Terminal UI library with rich, interactive
# widgets — written in Golang"** — the CANONICAL Go TUI library
# that PRECEDES bubbletea by 5+ years.  tview was created in 2018
# (bubbletea was started in 2020).  k9s — the most-starred Go TUI
# application at 33,783 GitHub stars — is built on tview.  tview
# is the de-facto TUI library for "we need a Kubernetes / database
# / LDAP / Discord / Mastodon / MangaDex TUI" projects in the Go
# ecosystem.
#
# tview's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. RETAINED-MODE WIDGET OBJECT GRAPH — tview applications are
#      built by INSTANTIATING widget objects that live for the
#      lifetime of the app and are mutated in place:
#
#          app := tview.NewApplication()
#          list := tview.NewList().
#              AddItem("Item 1", "Description", '1', func() {
#                  // handler
#              }).
#              AddItem("Item 2", "Description", '2', func() {
#                  // handler
#              })
#          app.SetRoot(list, true).Run()
#
#      Compare to bubbletea R531 (Elm Architecture — pure functions
#      threading immutable model) and ratatui R530 (immediate-mode
#      — widgets recreated every frame).  tview's retained-mode is
#      familiar to ANYONE who has written GTK, Qt, Swing, AWT,
#      WPF, AppKit, or any other 1990s-2010s GUI toolkit.  FIRST
#      documented Go TUI library with retained-mode widget object
#      graph semantics.
#
#   2. BUILT-IN WIDGET CATALOG — tview ships with 12 built-in
#      widgets covering most TUI needs:
#         * `Application`  — top-level event loop + screen owner
#         * `Box`          — base class for borders/title/padding
#         * `Button`       — clickable button
#         * `Checkbox`     — boolean toggle
#         * `DropDown`     — dropdown selector
#         * `Flex`         — flex-style layout container
#         * `Form`         — form with multiple input widgets
#         * `Frame`        — text frame around another widget
#         * `Grid`         — table-based layout
#         * `InputField`   — single-line text input
#         * `List`         — selectable list with handlers
#         * `Modal`        — modal dialog (button-row + message)
#         * `Pages`        — stacked-page container (navigation)
#         * `Table`        — 2D table with cell selection
#         * `TextArea`     — multi-line editable text
#         * `TextView`     — multi-line read-only text with ANSI
#                            color codes + scrolling
#         * `TreeView`     — hierarchical tree
#      Compare bubbletea's `bubbles` widget package (~12 widgets:
#      textinput, textarea, table, list, spinner, paginator,
#      progress, viewport, timer, stopwatch, key, help) and
#      ratatui's built-ins (~14: Block, Paragraph, List, Table,
#      Tabs, Gauge, Sparkline, BarChart, LineChart, Scrollbar,
#      Calendar, etc.).  tview's catalog is comparable in breadth
#      but more INHERITANCE-ORIENTED (Box is base class extended
#      by all widgets).
#
#   3. tcell BACKEND — tview is built on `gdamore/tcell` (an
#      undocumented dependency that is itself a major Go terminal
#      library).  tcell provides:
#         - Cell-grid abstraction (each terminal cell has rune +
#           foreground color + background color + style)
#         - Cross-platform input (keyboard + mouse + paste + resize)
#         - Cross-platform output (ncurses / Windows console /
#           termion-style ANSI)
#         - UTF-8 + grapheme cluster + double-width CJK awareness
#         - True-color (24-bit RGB) support with graceful 8-color
#           fallback for legacy terminals
#      Compare ratatui's `crossterm` / `termion` / `termwiz`
#      backend trait abstraction and bubbletea's tighter
#      crossterm dependency.  FIRST documented Go TUI library
#      that explicitly delegates terminal control to a separate
#      cell library (tcell).
#
#   4. EVENT-HANDLER CALLBACKS — Widgets register callbacks for
#      input events:
#         `list.SetSelectedFunc(func(index int, mainText, secondaryText string, shortcut rune) { ... })`
#         `app.SetInputCapture(func(event *tcell.EventKey) *tcell.EventKey { ... })`
#         `button.SetSelectedFunc(func() { ... })`
#      Compare bubbletea's `Update(msg tea.Msg) (tea.Model, tea.Cmd)`
#      pure-function pattern.  tview's callback model is the
#      RETAINED-MODE-equivalent — handlers fire when events arrive,
#      callbacks mutate widget state in place, the app loop
#      redraws.  FIRST documented Go library with widget-attached
#      callback event handlers.
#
#   5. PAGES + MODAL NAVIGATION — tview's `Pages` widget lets apps
#      stack multiple full-screen layouts and switch between them
#      with `pages.SwitchToPage("login")`, `pages.AddPage("help",
#      helpView, true, false)`, `pages.RemovePage("error-modal")`.
#      This is the TUI equivalent of single-page-application
#      navigation.  mangadesk uses Pages extensively: a main page,
#      a search page, a manga-detail page, a chapter-list page, a
#      download-options modal, an error modal.  FIRST documented
#      Go TUI library with first-class multi-page navigation.
#
# tview's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like `charmbracelet/bubbletea` R531 — full-screen TUI
#   * Like `gdamore/tcell` (undocumented dep) — terminal cell
#     abstraction
#   * Like `chzyer/readline` (documented elsewhere) — line-editing
#     primitives
#   * Unlike bubbletea R531 — RETAINED-MODE vs Elm Architecture.
#     tview widgets are objects that LIVE; bubbletea widgets are
#     strings produced by pure functions.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    `cursive` (Gyscos/cursive, retained-mode,
#                     predates ratatui by 2 years; would be the
#                     Rust parallel to tview)
#         * TS-Node: `blessed` (chjj/blessed, 2013 grandfather,
#                     retained-mode, predates ink by 4 years)
#     Adding cursive (Rust) and blessed (TS-Node) in future rounds
#     would complete the RETAINED-MODE TUI triple across the top
#     three languages, parallel to the immediate-mode/Elm/React
#     triple already documented in R530/R531/R532.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE mangadesk CLI — ZERO Flags, Pure tview TUI
#
# mangadesk's argv parser is THE Go stdlib (no library at all):
#
#     // main.go (verbatim, 12 lines)
#     package main
#
#     import (
#         "github.com/darylhjd/mangadesk/app/service"
#     )
#
#     func main() {
#         service.Start()
#         defer service.Shutdown()
#     }
#
# Zero `flag.NewFlagSet`, zero `os.Args` parsing, zero subcommand
# dispatch.  EVERYTHING happens via tview event handlers reading
# keystrokes inside the TUI.  This is an even more EXTREME version
# of the "minimal argv + rich TUI" pattern seen in R530 glim
# (Rust+ratatui, 2 flags), R531 yai (Go+bubbletea, 2 flags), and
# R532 kubelive (TS-Node+ink, 1 subcommand + 1 flag).  mangadesk
# has ZERO flags — the binary IS the TUI.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. RETAINED-MODE WIDGET OBJECT GRAPH — Every other documented
#      Go TUI library (bubbletea R531) uses pure-function rendering.
#      tview uses RETAINED-MODE: widgets are persistent objects
#      mutated in place by event handlers.  FIRST documented Go
#      retained-mode TUI library.
#
#   2. tcell BACKEND DELEGATION — Every other documented Go CLI
#      library handles terminal control directly (ANSI escape
#      emission, signal handling, raw mode).  tview delegates ALL
#      terminal control to `gdamore/tcell` — a separate library
#      with its own cell-grid abstraction.  FIRST documented Go
#      library with delegated terminal-cell backend.
#
#   3. EVENT-HANDLER CALLBACKS — Every other documented Go CLI
#      library uses imperative event loops (`for {...}`) or
#      bubbletea's pure-function Update.  tview uses widget-
#      attached callback functions (`SetSelectedFunc`,
#      `SetChangedFunc`, `SetInputCapture`).  FIRST documented Go
#      TUI library with retained-mode-equivalent callback events.
#
#   4. PAGES + MODAL NAVIGATION — Every other documented Go CLI
#      library is single-page (one main view).  tview's `Pages`
#      widget supports SPA-style multi-page navigation with
#      modal stacking.  FIRST documented Go library with first-
#      class multi-page TUI navigation.
#
#   5. INHERITANCE-BASED WIDGET HIERARCHY — Every other documented
#      Go CLI library uses Go composition (struct embedding).
#      tview uses Go-emulated INHERITANCE: `Box` is the base
#      "class" extended by all other widgets via embedded
#      pointer receiver methods.  FIRST documented Go library
#      with explicit inheritance-based widget hierarchy.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/darylhjd/mangadesk/blob/master/main.go — the
# binary takes NO arguments, all interaction is keyboard-driven
# inside the tview TUI.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

# mangadesk takes no command-line arguments — every interaction
# happens via keystrokes inside the tview TUI.  Only --help is
# supported by some shells' default behavior, but mangadesk itself
# does not handle it.

_arguments -s -S \
    && ret=0

return ret
